body_text.text:
While conceptually simple, epicurves are useful in many respects. They provide a simple, visual outline of epidemic dynamics, which can be used for assessing the growth or decline of an outbreak (
Barrett
et al., 2016;
Fitzgerald
et al., 2014;
Jernberg
et al., 2015;
Lanini
et al., 2014;
Nhan
et al., 2018) and therefore informing intervention measures (
Meltzer
et al., 2014;
WHO Ebola Response Team
et al., 2014;
WHO Ebola Response Team
et al., 2015). In addition, epicurves also form the raw material used by a range of modelling techniques for short-term forecasting (
Cori
et al., 2013;
Funk
et al., 2018;
Nouvellet
et al., 2018;
Viboud
et al., 2018) as well as in outbreak detection algorithms from syndromic surveillance data (
Farrington & Andrews, 2003;
Unkel
et al., 2012).
